🧭 The Correct Next Phases (In Order)
PHASE 1 — Lock Security Skeleton (Infrastructure)
Goal
Ensure every future controller is secure by default.
What to do

Replace Spring Security’s auto‑generated password with:

explicit configuration
explicit admin user definition


Confirm:

login required for all endpoints
logout works
session-based auth
no public APIs



Outcome
✅ You never have to retrofit security
✅ Every new feature is secure by default

This step is small but foundational.


PHASE 2 — Design Core Database Schema (V2 Migration)
Goal
Define the truth model for your application.
What to do
Create V2__core_tables.sql, including:

employee
document (ref + version, current flag)
training_instance
training_instance_employee (join)
training_instance_document (join)
audit_log

Decide explicitly:

PKs & FKs
NOT NULL rules
soft-delete flags
indexing strategy (for matrix queries)
UTF‑8 defaults
immutability guarantees

Outcome
✅ Database becomes authoritative
✅ Audit/compliance requirements enforced structurally
✅ Schema is versioned and reproducible

This is the most important technical step.


PHASE 3 — Map Entities to Existing Tables
Goal
Use Hibernate only as a mapping layer.
What to do

Create JPA entities that match the schema exactly
No auto DDL
No schema assumptions
No cascading surprises

Outcome
✅ Clean, predictable persistence
✅ Easy SQL debugging
✅ No “Hibernate magic” issues

PHASE 4 — Implement Audit Logging (Cross‑Cutting)
Goal
Ensure every data change is recorded automatically.
What to do

Define audit record structure
Implement:

service-layer audit hooks
or AOP-based audit capture


Log:

entity
operation
old/new state
user
timestamp



Outcome
✅ Compliance guarantee
✅ No forgotten audit logic
✅ Confidence in system integrity

